[36;1mNAME[0m
       pthreads - POSIX threads

[36;1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       POSIX.1  specifies  a  set  of interfaces (functions, header files) for
       threaded programming commonly known as POSIX threads, or  Pthreads.   A
       single process can contain multiple threads, all of which are executing
       the same program.  These threads share the same global memory (data and
       heap  segments),  but  each  thread  has its own stack (automatic vari‐
       ables).

       POSIX.1 also requires that threads share a range  of  other  attributes
       (i.e., these attributes are process‐wide rather than per‐thread):

       •  process ID

       •  parent process ID

       •  process group ID and session ID

       •  controlling terminal

       •  user and group IDs

       •  open file descriptors

       •  record locks (see [36;1mfcntl[22;0m(2))

       •  signal dispositions

       •  file mode creation mask ([36;1mumask[22;0m(2))

       •  current directory ([36;1mchdir[22;0m(2)) and root directory ([36;1mchroot[22;0m(2))

       •  interval timers ([36;1msetitimer[22;0m(2)) and POSIX timers ([36;1mtimer_create[22;0m(2))

       •  nice value ([36;1msetpriority[22;0m(2))

       •  resource limits ([36;1msetrlimit[22;0m(2))

       •  measurements of the consumption of CPU time ([36;1mtimes[22;0m(2)) and resources
          ([36;1mgetrusage[22;0m(2))

       As  well  as the stack, POSIX.1 specifies that various other attributes
       are distinct for each thread, including:

       •  thread ID (the [31;3;1mpthread_t[24;0m data type)

       •  signal mask ([36;1mpthread_sigmask[22;0m(3))

       •  the [31;3;1merrno[24;0m variable

       •  alternate signal stack ([36;1msigaltstack[22;0m(2))

       •  real‐time scheduling policy and priority ([36;1msched[22;0m(7))

       The following Linux‐specific features are also per‐thread:

       •  capabilities (see [36;1mcapabilities[22;0m(7))

       •  CPU affinity ([36;1msched_setaffinity[22;0m(2))

   [36;1mPthreads function return values[0m
       Most pthreads functions return 0 on success, and  an  error  number  on
       failure.   The error numbers that can be returned have the same meaning
       as the error numbers returned in [31;3;1merrno[24;0m by conventional system calls and
       C library functions.  Note that the pthreads functions do not  set  [31;3;1mer‐[0m
       [31;3;1mrno[24;0m.   For  each  of  the  pthreads functions that can return an error,
       POSIX.1‐2001 specifies that the function can never fail with the  error
       [36;1mEINTR[22;0m.

   [36;1mThread IDs[0m
       Each of the threads in a process has a unique thread identifier (stored
       in  the  type [31;3;1mpthread_t[24;0m).  This identifier is returned to the caller of
       [36;1mpthread_create[22;0m(3), and a thread can obtain its  own  thread  identifier
       using [36;1mpthread_self[22;0m(3).

       Thread  IDs are guaranteed to be unique only within a process.  (In all
       pthreads functions that accept a thread ID as an argument, that  ID  by
       definition refers to a thread in the same process as the caller.)

       The  system  may  reuse  a thread ID after a terminated thread has been
       joined, or a detached thread has terminated.  POSIX says: "If an appli‐
       cation attempts to use a thread ID whose lifetime has ended, the behav‐
       ior is undefined."

   [36;1mThread‐safe functions[0m
